				<img src="data:image/svg+xml;charset=utf-8,%3Csvg xmlns%3D'http%3A%2F%2Fwww.w3.org%2F2000%2Fsvg' viewBox%3D'0 0 1960 1351'%2F%3E"
		data-src=https://226391-691236-raikfcquaxqncofqfm.stackpathdns.com/thumbs/980x676r/photos/1524427486_346-31-green.jpg data-src-retina=https://226391-691236-raikfcquaxqncofqfm.stackpathdns.com/thumbs/1960x1351r/photos/1524427486_346-31-green.jpg
	 alt="346 - Green - Cacho-Negrete"
	 class="lazy">

									<figcaption>
																											<div class="photo-credit">
																			© <a href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/contributors/duncan-green">
											Duncan
																						Green
										</a>
																	</div>
																								</figcaption>
							</div>
			</div>
</figure>
</p>

<p class="dropcap">Is there an age at which you are no longer permitted to miss your mother? This longing, it seems, should fade with the years, yet as I&rsquo;ve grown older, I&rsquo;ve missed her more. I missed her when I received my master&rsquo;s degree. I missed her at my second wedding. I missed her at each son&rsquo;s graduation from college, and at their weddings. When my younger son made a film, and the audience rose up and applauded, I was back at the Yiddish Theater with my mother, with her whispering, &ldquo;How beautiful,&rdquo; in my ear. When my older son&rsquo;s <span class="smallcaps">CD</span> reaped good reviews, I saw her close her eyes with pleasure, humming the melody and insisting, &ldquo;He has <em>neshomeh</em> [beauty in his soul].&rdquo; I heard her brag at the birth of each of my grandchildren, &ldquo;Such a <em>shaineh maidel</em> [beautiful little girl].&rdquo; My throat clenched when I handed my grandchildren back to their mothers, but, ever my mother&rsquo;s child, I hid my tears.</p>

<p>I once believed it was the dead who were exiled, but now I understand it is the living. We long for what we can never have again. We are exiled from our loved ones, children banished to the foyer. I sit here with a solitary volume of our convoluted past, a story told from a single point of view. I wish the story were happier, the characters&rsquo; lives easier, the pages more filled with beauty. I wish the daughter and her mother had gone to the movies one last time before the end. I wish that when the mother asked from her hospital bed, &ldquo;Do you remember?&rdquo; the daughter hadn&rsquo;t denied it, but instead had leaned over and whispered, &ldquo;It&rsquo;s <span class="smallcaps">OK</span>, Ma. It was such a long time ago.&rdquo;</p>
														</div>


				
